Introduction

As we all may know thousands of people die every year due to Road Accidents and Accidents Data has been growing exponentional. Our job as Data Mining Engineers is to find as many rules as we can that better describes the main reasons that tell us: Why are those Accidents happening?. To accomplish that task were going to use the Apriori algorithm and were going to set minsup (minimum support) and minconf (minimum confidence) values to generate rules and were going to choose them looking for lift values grater than 1,1. Its very important to do this kind of work as we might find solutions to avoid so many accidents that are happening in the United Kingdom (2015).

As long as we were analysing our dataset, weve felt that some of the variables dont restrain our main goal: to find as much interesting rules as we can that show us why, when and how these accidentes are happening. As so, these were the variables that weve considered that we could remove:

  • Accident_Index - It was removed because its not important for the mining task to know the Accident_Index.
  • Location_Easting_OSGR - Weve decided to not keep any of accident location-related variable so all of them were removed, including Location_Northing_OSGR, Longitude, Latitude, LSOA_of_Accident_Location , Local_Authority_Highway and Local_Authority_District.
  • Locating_Northing_OSGR - Same reason as weve presented.
  • Longitude - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • Latitude - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • LSOA_of_Accident_Location - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • Local_Authority_Highway - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • Local_Authority_District - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • Police Force - Weve felt that any Police-related information wasnt important to our extracted data set.
  • 1st_Road_Class - Considering Roads characteristics, weve only selected Road_Type as a main item that describes Accidents road.
  • 1st_Road_Number - Weve considered that its more important to take care of Road_Type instead of Road_Number.
  • 2nd_Road_Class - Considering Roads characteristics, weve only selected Road_Type as a main item that describes Accidents road.
  • 2nd_Road_Number - Weve considered that its more important to take care of Road_Type instead of Road_Number.
  • Junction_Detail - Both Junction_Detail and Junction_Control are similar to Road_Type information so weve decided to delete them.
  • Junction_Control - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • Pedestrian_Crossing.Human_Control - Most of values were zero so weve decided that this column was not so relevant
  • Pedestrian_Crossing.Physical_Facilitiesl - Same reason as weve presented above.
  • Carriageway_Hazards - Most of values were none so weve also removed this column
  • Urban_or_Rural_Area - we havent considered this column so important for rules generation so weve removed it.
  • Did_Police_Officer_Attend_Scene_of_Accident - The presence of a Police officer at the scene of accident wont help us on finding patterns that explain why that same accident actually had happened. For that reason weve removed this variable.
  • Weather_Conditions - After a carefull analysis weve decided to remove this column because all values were zero so it wont affect so much our rules generation.

Pratical Work

Data Mining

Our Data Set contains multiples instances related to Accidents information. After an extended analysis and removing a lot of, what weve considered, unnecessary data, we can present our final result. Our final Data Set has information related to, for example, Date: We can observe that had happened more accidents during the 3rd Trimester.

Now were going to apply the Aprior algorithm on our Data Set and the following rules were obtained. The result is a set of 2724 rules. Were about to reduce the size of this set by adjusting minsup and minconf values. 

rules <- apriori(data_set,parameter=list(support=0.2, confidence=0.5))
rules

First were going to plot our data set and then analyse which range of confidence and support have the better rules (with a good lift value). 

plot(rules)

As we can observe, best rules have minsup values between [0.2 , 0.3], and minconf values between [0.8 , 1.0]. So, now were about to adjust our aprior algorithm by changing minsup and minconf values, and also by adding an extra option: minlen = 3 . This option allow us to choose rules with a minimum length of 3. 

rules <- apriori(data_set,parameter=list(support=0.25, confidence=0.85, minlen=3))

As we can see weve obtained a set of 653 rules, even though a lot less then 2724 we still need to adjust the apriori algorithm a little bit more. First things first, lets analyse our new set of rules by using a plot. 

plot(rules)

As we can observe, best rules have minsup values between [0.2 , 0.3], and minconf values between [0.9 , 1.0]. So, now were about to adjust our aprior algorithm by changing minsup and minconf values. 

rules <- apriori(data_set,parameter=list(support=0.25, confidence=0.9, minlen=3))

Weve obtained a set of 355 rules and were going to reduce this number by removing all redundant rules: if we have {A,B,C} => {D} and {A,B} => {D}, we can remove the second one because it derivates from the first one. 

rules<-rules[!is.redundant(rules)]
summary(rules)

By doing this step were able to reduce our set size in 49% !. Now we have a set of 181 rules.
Were going to analyse this new rule set by using a baloon plot: LHS (antecedent) on x-axis and RHS (consequent) on y-axis. Balloons color represent the aggregated interest measure in the group with a certain consequent, and balloons color shows the aggregated support.
Now were going to filter our rule set by lift using a value grater then 1.1 (lift > 1.1). The reason why weve used lift to filter our set is that with lift we can measure the performance of a targeting model (association rule). So for values of lift greater then 1 we can ensure that they are independent (antecedent and consequent).

So lets filter our rule set. 

subrules <- rules[quality(rules)$lift >= 1.1]
summary(subrules)
plot(subrules)

Only 53 rules are present in our rule set and all of them are good one with a good lift value. Lets use a plot using support and lift instead of support and confidence (lift on y-axis). 

plot(rules, measure=c("support", "lift"), shading="confidence")

Now were about to order our rule set by lift and plot it using a Two-key plot. Here order represents, for example, the number of items in a rule. 

plot(rules, shading="order", control=list(main = "Two-key plot"))

After using a matrix plot method using the following command,plot(subrules, method=matrix, measure=lift), were able to obtain an output of our rule set:

Conclusion

During this assignment weve always tried to simplify the view of our rule set. One of our main problems resides on the Apriori Algorithm: As much as we try to generate good enough rules this algorithm had always generated rules with only one consequent (RHS), even though we had changed minsup and minconf values. To avoid this issue weve decided to present 10 random rules and 10 rules that were chosen by us.
